When Daniel Ortega attained the presidency of Nicaragua for the first time, he did it through dictatorial procedures. Both he and Samuel Lazo were elected with less than 50% of the votes. His term was also marred by internal political strife and a difficult economic climate. His policies of nationalizing all of the private banks and curtaining almost all expressions of media were both failures. After just one term, Daniel Ortega was forced to step down.

After a 10 year hiatus, Daniel Ortega was able to rebound and again win the presidential elections. Ortega has kept his re-election promise by not holding presidential elections until 2006, and completed his term of office in January, 2007.

These 27 years of authoritarian rule have earned Daniel Ortega the nickname of "Stalin extraordinary of Latin America". Additionally, during this period, the poverty level of the Nicaraguan people has dropped from 80% to 48%.
